Prisma & migrations

Layout (source of truth)

prisma.config.ts (repo root) defines the app datasource (DIRECT_URL via env), schema at prisma/schema (multi-file.prisma), and migrations at prisma/migrations.
The generator in prisma/schema/base.prisma outputs the client to src/generated/prisma.
test/prisma/ holds an additional schema tree and migrations for tests/assessment—same rules apply when editing there.

Domain-first schema files (required)

When adding a new product/domain area, create a dedicated Prisma schema file under prisma/schema/ for that domain instead of appending everything to an unrelated file.
Examples:
- AI chat history/messages -> prisma/schema/ai.prisma
- Billing -> prisma/schema/billing.prisma
- Keep auth/account models in prisma/schema/user.prisma

Do not mix unrelated domains in one file when a separate domain file is appropriate. Cross-file relations are expected and allowed in multi-file Prisma schemas.

What the agent may do

Edit Prisma model files under the relevant schema/ folder(s).
Add or edit SQL under migrations/<timestamp>\_<name>/migration.sql (or new migration folders) when schema changes require it.
Keep naming and structure consistent with existing migrations in the repo.
When introducing relations, explicitly review delete behavior and choose whether onDelete: Cascade is needed (required review step, not optional).

Cascade review checklist (required)

For every new or changed relation:
- Decide if child rows are meaningless without parent row (ownership relation). If yes, use onDelete: Cascade.
- If child rows must be preserved independently, do not use Cascade; choose Restrict/NoAction/SetNull as appropriate.
- Validate both direct and transitive deletes (e.g. User -> Chat -> Message).
- Reflect that choice in both Prisma schema and SQL migration constraints.

What the user runs (do not execute from the agent)

Do not run commands that apply schema to the database, including: prisma migrate dev, prisma migrate deploy, prisma db push, prisma migrate reset, or equivalent.
After changing schema or migrations, tell the user what changed and that they should apply migrations locally or in their pipeline—do not run those commands yourself.

Client generation

prisma generate (e.g. npm run prisma:generate / bun run prisma:generate per package.json) updates the generated client under src/generated/prisma; it is not the same as applying migrations to the DB.
Only run generate if the user explicitly asks or the task clearly requires a fresh client; otherwise the user or CI may run it.

Prisma query style (default)

Prefer Prisma Client queries (findUnique/findMany/create/update/upsert/delete, select/include, transactions) over raw SQL.
Avoid prisma.$queryRaw and prisma.$queryRawUnsafe as much as possible.
Use raw queries only when Prisma Client cannot express the required operation cleanly or efficiently, and keep that usage minimal, documented, and parameterized safely.
